I"Y<p><span class="newthought">These notes</span> are for BINF 4003 - Methods III: Symbolic Methods, taught in the Fall of 2019 at Columbia University.</p>

<h2 id="overview">Overview</h2>

<ol>
  <li>
    <p><a href="introduction">Introduction</a>: What are symbolic methods? Data-Information-Knowledge hierarchy, semantic interoperability, “curly braces problem”.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><a href="knowl-rep">Knowledge representation</a>: Medical knowledge representations, closed vs open world assumptions, reference vs interface terminologies.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><a href="desiderata">Desiderata for medical vocabularies</a>: Characteristics of high-quality controlled medical vocabularies.</p>
  </li>
</ol>

<h2 id="specific-terminologies-and-tools">Specific terminologies and tools</h2>

<ol>
  <li>
    <p><a href="snomed">SNOMED</a>: Design, structure, limitations, adoption, SNOMED clinical terms (SNOMED-CT).</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><a href="icd">ICD</a>: Design, structure, limitations, adoption, versions: ICD-9, ICD-10, ICD-11.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><a href="umls">UMLS</a>: Three knowledge sources: Metathesaurus, Semantic Network, SPECIALIST Lexicon and Lexical Tools. Purpose, data sources, use cases.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><a href="rxnorm">RxNorm</a>: Design, structure, data sources, use cases. RxNorm vs RxTerm.</p>
  </li>
</ol>

